    <entry xml:lang="en">
        <title>Kobo eBook Case: Ideas&#x2F;Preliminary</title>
        <published>2025-01-28T00:00:00+00:00</published>
        <updated>2025-01-28T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
        
        <author>
          <name>
            
              Unknown
            
          </name>
        </author>
        
        <link rel="alternate" type="text/html" href="https://berdandy.com/blog/ebook-wetforming/"/>
        <id>https://berdandy.com/blog/ebook-wetforming/</id>
        
        <content type="html" xml:base="https://berdandy.com/blog/ebook-wetforming/">&lt;p&gt;My wife and I both got Kobo eBooks for ourselves, but she was unhappy with the stock case options. When I got into
leatherworking, I offered to make her a custom one once I had figured out how to not make terrible things.&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are a few options I explored:&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Slipcover. Decided against, because it&#x27;s not a permanent case.&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Corner-grips. Decided aginst, because one corner would block the charging port.&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Velcro-mount for a floating effect. Decided against, aesthetic reasons.&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Wet-formed grips. This seems the most workable option.&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;ul&gt;
&lt;hr &#x2F;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After some digging, I finally found a random photo of someone who had done a similar thing, so I was confident
I wasn&#x27;t completely off the mark. I wet-formed top-and-bottom &quot;grips&quot; for a test, and rough-cut material for a cover.&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;center&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;&#x2F;pages&#x2F;wip&#x2F;case_grips_cover.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;img src=&quot;https:&#x2F;&#x2F;berdandy.com&#x2F;pages&#x2F;wip&#x2F;case_grips_cover.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;case_grips_cover&quot; width=&quot;480&quot; height=&quot;240&quot; loading=&quot;lazy&quot; &#x2F;&gt;&lt;&#x2F;a&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;center&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I can picture it now.&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;hr &#x2F;&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The remaining plan is:&lt;&#x2F;p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Cut a &quot;reversed&quot; cover pocket to accommodate a passport. A strong secondary use for this case is a passport holder.&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Cut a pen holder to sit in snap loop (or spine?)&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Assemble with temporary tape&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Cut cover to shape, including snap loop&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Finish raw leather grips (cover and pocket material is already-finished leather)&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Finish all interior edges&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Assemble with grips and cover pocket and final trim&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Finish exterior edges&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Attach snap closure&lt;&#x2F;li&gt;
&lt;&#x2F;ol&gt;
</content>
        
